Introduction
\layout Standard

Ding Dong Doorentry Systems Ltd.
 (DDDS) has commissioned our group to develop an idea for a new product.
 Their existing product market is centred on low-technology but robust door
 entry systems for stair doors.
 They would like to move into production of high specification door entry
 systems and, in particular, see a potential market that takes advantage
 of the fact that most small companies and many households now own a personal
 computer.
 The concept that DDDS has proposed is to use the screen and sound facilities
 already present on PC's, in combination with a remote door control unit.
 The intention is to sell a door entry system that allows a person within
 the premises to use a PC to view and communicate with the person at the
 door.
 In addition, the fact that all PC's are supplied with serial ports allows
 the PC to provide these functions whilst being situated away from the door
 itself.
 The remote door control unit would be sold together with the necessary
 PC software.
 
\layout Standard

As a further development of the concept, DDDS have proposed having automated
 entry control, such that entry can be gained without an operator being
 present at the PC.
 They have suggested that this could be done by operating the door with
 a combination of some kind of personal card or key, and a PIN number.
\layout Standard

We have been commissioned to produce a demonstration prototype of this product.
 In doing this, we have refined the initial specification for the product,
 and decided on the best way to provide the facilities that DDDS wants to
 see.
 This report outlines the findings of our market research, the design decisions
 which we have taken, and identifies the additional features that could
 increase the product's marketability.
 
