Typically these properties do not have a remote door entry system such as
 an intercom.
 A major reason for this is that existing security measures, such as mechanical
 locks and door peep-holes, are far cheaper and more reliable.
 Systems such as intercoms tend to be used where the distance from the door
 to the operator is significant, but in this sort of residential property,
 a visitor can expect to be met at the front door.
 Therefore, the market in this sector is extremely limited.
 
\layout Standard

A more likely market in this area would be properties sited within large
 grounds, which can have entrances that are set a significant distance away
 from the property.
 These properties could use the improved security of visual communication,
 and the added convenience of being able to identify visitors from inside
 the property.
 However, there is once again a number of drawbacks of the proposed system.
 Primarily, the use of a PC as the control device conflicts with typical
 patterns of PC use in a domestic environment, namely that it would need
 to be powered up for most of the time.
 It would also need to be in an easily accessed location, such as a hallway,
 and would therefore need to be as small and discrete as possible.
 Existing intercom and videophone solutions have recognised this, and have
 produced products no bigger than a conventional telephone.
 
\layout Subsection

Conclusion
\layout Standard

In the residential market sector, it is clear that the proposed system has
 a number of significant drawbacks.
 Existing products provide both audio and video functionality, and at a
 moderate cost.
 The lack of uniformity of PC ownership means that such a system is an immediate
 non-starter in shared stair environments.
 Furthermore, the cost of providing a PC as part of the package would negate
 any potential cost saving inherent in the system concept.
 What the domestic residential market really wants is reliable, low cost
 technology that is easy to use, convenient and discrete.
 On these grounds, the proposed system would be unable to compete with products
 already on the market.
 Our research findings backs this up; the majority of people are quite happy
 with their present system.
