NHS 
\layout Standard

The needs of hospital security, like school security, vary with the location
 and the circumstances.
 While most wards are open-access, there remains a need for security in
 many areas of hospital buildings.
 For example, recent media attention has highlighted the inadequacies of
 the security measures in some maternity wards; our system has the potential
 to rectify these deficiencies.
 Other areas, such as medicine cupboards and supply stores, and areas which
 are staff-only also require some form of restriction on access.
 Again, our system is tailored to these demands.
 
\layout Standard

Government inquiries into hospital security, prompted by a spate of `baby-snatch
ing' incidents in the early 1990s, identified some existing NHS security
 measures as being insufficient.
 Among the most salient points made in these reports were:
\layout Itemize

video security cameras are often left unmonitored
\layout Itemize

automated security being bypassed by people who pretend to be someone else
\layout Standard

The proposed system would have to be highly reliable and easy to use; the
 nature of the hospital environment is such that some existing technologies,
 such as magnetic swipe cards, are liable to failure (in this case from
 magnetic fields generated by scanning equipment).
 As there may be emergency situations where time is critical, and where
 access to a particular area is suddenly more important than security, a
 hospital system would need to have some form of manual override which could
 be operated from either side of the door.
 This could operate in tandem with an alarm system, to prevent abuse of
 the override facility.
