\layout Subsection

The proposed software
\layout Standard

The software should be user-friendly, and simple to use.
 It must not confront the user with a bewildering array of options just
 to open a door.
 It was decided that, to make the system a bit more robust, that there should
 be relatively little indispensable communication between the Motorola board
 and the PC during normal operation, and that the only information that
 is actually required is that video data be sent so that a user-interface
 running on the PC would be able to display a recent image of the doorway.
 The automatic operation portion of the system runs exclusively on the board
 and doesn't require any intervention from the PC.
 The only reason that the PC needs to be used for the automatic entry system
 is for maintenance of the user database, which is downloaded onto the board
 whenever the latter is initialised or the main database on the PC is updated.
 
\layout Standard

The software is the primary focus for introducing the `value-added' components
 that would make a system such as this worthwhile and more marketable.
 For example, the Motorola board could keep a log of the iButtons which
 are used; this could then be downloaded onto the PC and stored for security
 purposes.
 If the PC is on, the main database could be used to store an image of the
 iButton's holder, so that when the board is used to open the door, an operator
 at the PC could see a picture of the person who should be at the door.
 If the person using the iButton does not match the stored picture, the
 operator could intervene.
\layout Standard

Another idea would be to allow visitors to leave voicemail messages on the
 system, if they came to the door but there was no one there to let them
 in.
 This could be extended to include a still image or a short video sequence
 of the person at the door.
\layout Standard

For added security, the PC could be left on and set to save the video sequence
 to disc.
 This would give a CCTV-like functionality to the package.
\layout Standard

The main reason for developing a system such as this would be to make full
 use of the flexibility of the PC software; once the basic functionality
 of door control and audio/video data transmission has been created, much
 greater functionality can be added at little extra cost.
 The source code could even be sold as part of the system, so that the more
 adventurous owner of the package could extend it themselves; although the
 target market may not lend itself to this approach.
 This purpose may better be served by adding an external programming port
 into the software, so that the main system maintains integrity, but the
 end-user can extend its functionality.
 For example, hooks in our database system could allow the user to create
 a database of their own that was more tailored to their own requirements;
 the system provides the basic mechanism for identifying people but then
 the owner can add extra services such as voicemail retrieval.
 This would also allow for further development and sales by DDDS as they
 could then sell extension packages for the system designed to increase
 functionality.
\layout Standard

Another useful feature would be remote administration.
 This could be achieved for instance by replacing the client software with
 a custom-built web server
