The proposed system in a wider context
\layout Standard

The benefits of using a unique, highly portable key device to operate the
 door system can be translated to other areas with security needs.
 Potentially, the iButton system can control access to any electronic device,
 or control access via some electronic control system.
 For example, access to a photocopier can easily and cheaply controlled
 using the same iButton that allows access to a building.
 It can be used to control access to computers, and the data held within
 them, which of particular importance in a hospital environment.
 
\layout Standard

A further benefit of such a widespread use of iButton tags is that, using
 a central database of request actions, personnel can be tracked through
 buildings and located relatively easily.
 In a hospital environment, this is particularly useful, and would complement
 the existing use of pagers.
 In schools, iButton technology can be extended to incorporate a payment
 system for school meals, and could also form the basis of an electronic
 attendance register.
 The real benefit of an electronic key such as this is that it minimises
 the number of PIN numbers, keys and magnetic cards that have to be carried
 around; one key covers a multitude of uses.
\layout Standard

In the interviews with representatives from schools, a common theme was
 reliability; in particular, potential buyers were keen to know the expected
 lifespan of the product.
 For iButton devices, manufacturer's data indicates the expected lifespan
 at 10 years.
 This is well in excess of the typical lifespan of magnetic card devices,
 which is usually around 2 years.
 For the remainder of the lock control hardware, the lifespan depends on
 the environment in which it is installed.
 The external hardware, consisting of the iButton reader, the doorbell button
 and the keypad, is mechanically and electronically simple, and provided
 ruggedised versions are used, they should outlast the iButton devices.
