 to automatically unlock the door.
\layout Subsubsection

Power failure
\layout Standard

When then the system stops working the premises will be unaffected as the
 backup mechanical operation of the lock will allow it to have the same
 security level as at present.
 Additionally, exit is still possible, again by using the mechanical exit
 mechanism.
 The electromagnetic latch mechanism can be specified as defaulting to the
 open state, so that total power failure does not lock people in or out.
\layout Subsubsection

Partial system failure
\layout Standard

With the failure of part of the system, the redundancy in the design should
 allow the rest of the system to remain operational.
 If the remote PC is not operating, the door control unit has enough local
 processing power to keep the automatic mode of operation running.
 Conversely, failure of part of the automatic system, for example the keypad
 or iButton, does not affect the operation of the manual (intercom and video)
 mode.
